🎬 DVD Rental Business Analysis — Sakila SQL Project
About the Dataset
Sakila is a sample database provided by MySQL representing a DVD rental store business. It contains 16 interconnected tables covering customers, films, actors, rentals, payments, inventory, and stores — making it ideal for practicing real-world multi-table SQL analysis.
Tools Used

MySQL
MySQL Workbench

Business Questions Answered

What is the total revenue generated from all payments?
Who are the top 10 customers by total spending?
Who are the top 10 customers by full name and total spending?
Which film categories are rented the most?
What are the top 5 most rented films?
Which film category generates the highest revenue?
Which actors appeared in the most films?
How much revenue did each store generate?
What is the allowed rental duration by category?
What is the actual rental duration by category based on customer behavior?
Which customers have never rented a film?
Who are the VIP customers based on total spending?
Which film category is the best performing by revenue?
Which customers are High Value vs Low Value based on average spending?
What is the monthly revenue trend?
Which film category is most profitable in each store?

Skills Demonstrated

Multi-table JOINs (up to 5 tables)
LEFT JOIN with NULL filtering
CTEs (Common Table Expressions)
Window Functions (RANK, PARTITION BY)
Aggregate Functions (SUM, AVG, COUNT)
Date Functions (MONTHNAME, YEAR)
CASE WHEN with subqueries
GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY

Key Insights

Sports is the most rented film category with 1,179 rentals, also generating the highest revenue of $5,314.21
Store 2 outperforms Store 1 with a total revenue of $33,924.06
July 2005 was the peak revenue month with $28,368.91, indicating strong seasonal demand mid-year
A small group of high value customers contribute disproportionately to total revenue compared to low value customers







